35
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Judge Carter, you're a child of the great migration.

36
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Tell us about where and when you were born and how you came to come north.

37
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:32,000
I was born in Carreyville, Florida.

38
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:52,000
When I was very young, after my mother birthed me, I was a part of my migration and family,

39
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:01,000
out of the deep south to the north and that broke my migration.

40
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:07,000
My family was born free.

41
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:17,000
I think maybe about 60 years after the Civil War.

42
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:26,000
We were a free, free blocks coming out of the south.

43
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
I regret my migration.

44
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And what year was that?

45
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,000
What year were you born?

46
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:42,000
I was born in 1917.

47
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:46,000
In Carreyville, I said, or earlier, Carreyville, Florida.

48
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Where did your family move to?

49
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Your father was already up north.

50
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:02,000
My father had, my mother was in Florida, birthed me.

51
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:15,000
I think that he was, or they were part of the migrant agricultural families.

52
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:30,000
But because of the war, I hear probably had some charisma, or was a man who was a man

53
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:37,000
who was just not a peon on, but he had some intelligence.

54
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:48,000
He had sent him north, and he was working in a factory.

55
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:56,000
After my mother birthed me, she joined him in the rest of the farm in Newark.

56
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:04,000
What are your earliest memories about growing up in Newark?

57
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:25,000
Well, I was, my father died when I was a year old, and my mother had no special education.

58
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
She was not an ex-wife woman.

59
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
She had some schooling.

60
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:45,000
But she did not have enough schooling to get a job, other than as a washing clothes for white people.

61
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:55,000
And as she did to keep bread on the table for us.

62
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And I lived with her by President Standards and poverty until I was 12.

63
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:19,000
When I was 12 years old, my older sister married.

64
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:29,000
She was a woman who sold and made clothes.

65
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:39,000
And she married this man who owned the bar in London, New Jersey.

66
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:53,000
And that was sort of like a big coming out of poverty.

67
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:00,000
She insisted that he remain at all the family of the together.

68
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
So she lived with him.

69
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:11,000
And the family all together and not enabled us to get better housing.

70
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:19,000
And every time we sort of moved, it was to improve our living conditions.

71
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:38,000
After I was 12 years old, I became, for the first time, with her marriage, I was able to have a birth room for myself.

72
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:42,000
So I ended up toilet and I was back.

73
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Until that time, I had to use outhouses with other people.

74
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:02,000
I remember that I was such a state.

75
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:08,000
Fortunately, it was sort of hard marrying this man.

76
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:24,000
It was sort of like the period when I was known as White Fair Hotel, when this spoke about marriage is rich man.

77
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:36,000
And it was similar to that because it opened the door to me to mainstream parabatives.

78
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:48,000
I had never been an indoors toilet and stuff like that.

79
00:08:48,000 --> 00:09:15,000
All of the, what I learned about the difference between the poor and the rich, for example, is poor people never or rarely learn what they need to know.

80
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:24,000
Because I live middle class people, can't live on the streets and stuff like that.

81
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:31,000
But when it comes time, but they need to know something, they know where to get it.

82
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:53,000
And second thing, the poor and the rich, is that the poor people, poor people, act out there, live on the streets.

83
00:09:53,000 --> 00:10:01,000
Middle class people do the same thing but behind doors.

84
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:12,000
They do not, they have porches or stuff, and they do not have to live their life on the street.

85
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:36,000
So when I was a boy in the street, which was once the worst storms in the ghetto, it has been rehabilitated or what you call it.

86
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:54,000
Because now the city of Newark has redone boys with one of the worst storms in the ghetto.

87
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:06,000
But I was rejected, I did, what of that, you call that doing?

88
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Well, education, you wrote in your memoir that your desire for education, early on, inspired you.

89
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:25,000
What, I mean, schooling and education, what opened you up to that in the way that you went ahead and you didn't see it so well?

90
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:34,000
I was not skillful with my hands.

91
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:52,000
I knew that somehow I was going to find a way into the mainstream and get an education and find my way there.

92
00:11:52,000 --> 00:12:04,000
And what I recognized was the only way I could do that was a good education.

93
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:19,000
I was considered smart and I skipped at skipped school and stuff like that.

94
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And that was an advantage to me. And also I read a lot on discipline reading, but at the same time it exposed me to a lot of ideas and stuff.

95
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:51,000
And I knew somehow I had to be in the mainstream, find my way to the mainstream or else I would not survive.

96
00:12:51,000 --> 00:13:06,000
And so I recognized that. And I spent a lot of time in the library at a public library close by.

97
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:27,000
Unfortunately, my reading was on discipline. I like to read novels, history, historic novels and stuff.

98
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:51,000
But at some times some real hard discipline reading I would do. But for the most part it was not the kind of hard, noves reading that forms a brilliant mind.

99
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:56,000
But anyway, I had to read the helps.

100
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:03,000
What were schools like in Newark and then in East Orange? What were the schools like?

101
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:07,000
Were they integrated?

102
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:22,000
No, Newark was when I was in Newark, my entire 12 years old, that was where we were in poverty.

103
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:37,000
And the people from the South, the migration from the South, was from my sisters were at the age of poultry.

104
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:52,000
My mother was very worried that they would, the gods would ask them, that they would be in the park and hide it or go on.

105
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:57,000
And she wanted to desperately get out of there.

106
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:26,000
And when my sister named me married, this guy had this bar on grill, she was able to satisfy that because the gods would be on the street after my sisters who at that time were 16 and so.

107
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:40,000
And she was certain that they might be in pregnant and suffered for a word of love.

108
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:47,000
And of course, she showed a double-sided cause I had more freedom.

109
00:15:47,000 --> 00:16:01,000
She was not worried about me and proglating anybody, but she should have been that concerned, she was not.

110
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:09,000
When did you become aware of race?

111
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:37,000
I think early on when I was in maybe the sixth grade or so, we had two girls in the class who were friends, white girl and the black girl.

112
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:51,000
And I remember this to this day, the white girl had bangs and she fell from her back.

113
00:16:51,000 --> 00:17:00,000
The black girl had braids and she would go to her hairpipe where she tried to.

114
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:15,000
She was a very close friend and at one point, the black girl and she and the black girl and the orange one.

115
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:25,000
The white girl went to the teacher and complained and the teacher had no sympathy for her.

116
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:29,000
She told her you should stay with your own kind.

117
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:40,000
She told me how the prejudice affected itself.

118
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:52,000
But this was in the nook school and even though the teacher said that to this white girl, had no sympathy for her.

119
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:02,000
When I was in New York, they schooled and stayed back and allowed things to play out.

120
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:16,000
When I was in East Orange school, they were at birth to any black white intercourse.

121
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:20,000
They looked at it all and they interviewed.

122
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:33,000
And what that showed me is that the very faces of prejudice, I'm sure that my teachers in East Orange,

123
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:50,000
now I know, were as concerned about as maybe as prejudice as the teachers in East Orange were, proofs of it.

124
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:54,000
But they stood back and let things play out.

125
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:02,000
And so what that showed me is how white prejudice has very strong.

126
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:16,000
The East Orange people intervened and wanted segregation to be imposed.

127
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:24,000
They couldn't do it by law anymore, but they wanted it imposed.

128
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:39,000
All the people, the teachers in New York were not that they were concerned, I guess, but they didn't appear.

129
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:51,000
You had very different experience in your book at Burrington High School, where you went for two years, and then you went to East Orange High School in your third year of high school.

130
00:19:51,000 --> 00:20:02,000
Did you talk about, I think, a good example that you write about, what happened around the swimming pool, how it was organized, how it changed, and what your role was in that.

131
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:31,000
I don't know, I don't remember what great I was in now, but at one point, what would happen in gym and gym classes was that we had gym babies.

132
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:38,000
We had gym maybe three or four times a week.

133
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:47,000
We would play basketball, and I would say some callous medicine basketball.

134
00:20:47,000 --> 00:21:01,000
And then, part of the class, the white kids would go down to the pool and either swim or learn to swim.

135
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:08,000
The blacks would not allow us to use the pool except on all of a sudden, we can't.

136
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:26,000
When the sexes, all the black women or girls would use the pool after class, and then the pool was clean.

137
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:38,000
The other week, again, the black boys would use the pool, and then the pool was cleaned out.

138
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:55,000
There was a ruling from the Supreme Court of Literacy that all the facilities had to be secreted.

139
00:21:55,000 --> 00:22:02,000
All the school facilities had to be open to all people.

140
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:11,000
For that knowledge, I decided I was going to use the pool.

141
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:23,000
I don't know how I learned that I must have read the newspaper.

142
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:30,000
What was the story made?

143
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:38,000
I read this to bed about it.

144
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:53,000
What made it so absurd was that I couldn't swim.

145
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:04,000
I would have to go to the pool every day that was gym class when the white boys went down.

146
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:12,000
Once I went to the white boys, I stayed out of the pool. Nobody was in the pool with me.

147
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:21,000
I couldn't swim or scared to death, even a few feet of water because I didn't know.

148
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:34,000
I was in the pool alone during the class. I couldn't get any of the other blocks of joining me.

149
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:48,000
After that semester, I was threatened by the teachers that were going to experiment and I refused to run.

150
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:58,000
They pleaded with me to not do this, to stay on the floor like the others.

151
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:14,000
But my feeling was that I was entitled to use that pool that I was my right to use it.

152
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:23,000
If I had been white, that time, even if I couldn't swim was not the issue.

153
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:29,000
They would be teaching me to swim. They were teaching white kids who couldn't swim.

154
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:33,000
That was the time they were taught them to swim.

155
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:45,000
It was a very stressful time for me.

156
00:24:45,000 --> 00:25:00,000
The result was that instead of allowing everybody to use the pool and opening it, they closed it.

157
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:15,000
The blood was a bad feature for the school. Each time I had one of the best swimming teams in the city.

158
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:19,000
I was winning a lot of tournaments and stuff like that.

159
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:30,000
But it decided that instead of opening the pool, everybody that would close it.

160
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:40,000
That showed me the great cost to white of segregation. They paid a price for it.

161
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:57,000
You enrolled at Lincoln University in Pennsylvania when you were 16. How did you come to Lincoln University?

162
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:06,000
Well, I skipped a lot of classes. I was considered very bright.

163
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:14,000
I was a very good test doctor.

164
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:26,000
I was a good fitter by testing for anybody else in Lincoln class.

165
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:32,000
Now, I was considered brilliant.

166
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:35,000
I guess I can accept that.

167
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:42,000
But it seems to me that that's a gift too.

168
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:47,000
To learn to take tests.

169
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:57,000
That's not necessarily mean intellectual gifts.

170
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:07,000
But at the time, because I was so good, I was considered as a intellectual gifted.

171
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:11,000
I'll accept that.

172
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:15,000
What was Lincoln like at Lincoln University?

173
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:21,000
What was it like to be a student at Lincoln University?

174
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:32,000
The Lincoln University was a great experience of me.

175
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:42,000
I really had such a wonderful time there.

176
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:53,000
It was isolated and off the high-brewed path.

177
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:06,000
We spent a lot of time together to friends, my friends and I.

178
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:20,000
I was not interested at that time in the hard sciences.

179
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:28,000
What I was interested in was the social sciences.

180
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:46,000
While I was in the laboratory and so forth, I'd be looking out wanting to be on the campus playing ball.

181
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:56,000
It was really one of the very great times in my life.

182
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:10,000
I was so happy to have friends and people there because we were so isolated.

183
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:14,000
It was the first time you would have predominantly black educational environment.

184
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:19,000
Did that have something to do with it?

185
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:34,000
What I learned, however, was that it was not the school.

186
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:44,000
It was a time when I had all my friends and people there.

187
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:51,000
I went back some time later with the sport was going.

188
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:58,000
How did your time at Lincoln prepare you for civil rights activism, do you think?

189
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:12,000
When we were at Lincoln, we were an old male school.

190
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:36,000
And it's professors were former professors, retired from Princeton.

191
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:59,000
The head of the provost of one of the years of Lincoln was Princeton graduate.

192
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:16,000
They never, the Lincoln member at that time, very bored, we were good drunk and chair things down and so forth.

193
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:27,000
There was no effort to curb this and when we came along, we thought that this was being

194
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:41,000
preserved or listed, that the faculty was, that they sort of condoned this as a way that was had to be accepted

195
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:48,000
because black, black, when I'm unable to control them so.

196
00:31:48,000 --> 00:32:07,000
So my generation of school felt that we ought to be able to control ourselves.

197
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:14,000
We didn't have to be breaking up things and stuff like that.

198
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:20,000
We were young men, supposed to be educated.

199
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:33,000
And so we should not tolerate this boring behavior that was being exhibited by an unacceptable.

200
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:42,000
We started agitating for black faculty, for more blacks, on the faculty.

201
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:56,000
There was only one professor, a English black on the faculty, all the rest of the people were white.

202
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:00,000
We began agitating for that.

203
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:07,000
I think, and we, was on the debating, was on the debating team.

204
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:23,000
And we had debates for the small colleges like Habba Food and not the Ivy League schools and colleges were just below that.

205
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:39,000
And I think what that did for me was to enable me to not fear competing with white.

206
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:51,000
That gave me some courage and understanding that I could be, I was, compete with white people.

207
00:33:51,000 --> 00:34:08,000
Which is one of the problems at that time that blacks, blacks have the whole head because they were stereotypes.

208
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:15,000
The worst about being able to compete with white people.

209
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:21,000
But that was a good time in my life that I learned.

210
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:24,000
That was helpful.

211
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:29,000
How did you come to choose to go to Howard Law School?

212
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:30,000
How did I come?

213
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:33,000
From Lincoln, you went to Howard.

214
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:43,000
I was, I went to Howard Law School on scholarship.

215
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:50,000
One of the people was recruited.

216
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:58,000
And I had never thought I could be a good lawyer because of my voice.

217
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:01,000
I don't have a good voice.

218
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:07,000
And I thought a good lawyer had to have a big voice.

219
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:12,000
And you know, it was a claim.

220
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:18,000
But I found that you didn't have to do that to be a decent lawyer.

